        "           Plurality voting is an ": null
    },
    {
        "electoral system": "Electoral System"
    },
    {
        " in which each voter is allowed to vote for only one candidate, and the candidate who polls the most among their counterparts  is elected. In a system based on ": null
    },
    {
        "single-member district": "Single-Member District"
    },
    {
        "s, it may be called  first-past-the-post  , single-choice voting, simple plurality or relative/simple majority. In a system based on multi-member districts, it may be referred to as winner-takes-all or ": null
    },
    {
        "bloc voting": "Plurality-At-Large Voting"
    },
    {
        ". The system is often used to elect members of a legislative assembly or executive officers. It is the most common form of the system, and is used in most elections in the United States, the lower house  in India, elections to the ": null
    },
    {
        "House of Commons": "House Of Commons"
    },
    {
        " and English local elections in the United Kingdom.     Plurality voting is distinguished from a majoritarian electoral system, in which, to win, a candidate must receive an ": null
    },
    {
        "absolute majority": "Absolute Majority"
    },
    {
        " of votes, i.e., more votes than all other candidates combined. Both systems may use ": null
    },
    {
        "single-member": "Single-Member District"
    },
    {
        " or multi-member constituencies. In the latter case it may be referred to as an exhaustive counting system: one member is elected at a time and the process repeated until the number of vacancies is filled.     In some jurisdictions, including France and some of the United States including ": null
    },
    {
        "Louisiana": "Louisiana"
    },
    {
        " and ": null
    },
    {
        "Georgia": "Georgia"
    },
    {
        ", a two-ballot or runoff election plurality system is used. This may require ": null
    },
    {
        "two rounds": "Two-Round System"
    },
    {
        " of voting. If on the first round no candidate receives over 50% of the votes, then a second round takes place, with just the two highest-voted candidates in the first round. This ensures that the winner gains a majority of votes in the second round. Alternatively, all candidates above a certain threshold in the first round may compete in the second round. If there are more than two candidates standing, then a plurality vote may decide the result.     In ": null
    },
    {
        "political science": "Political Science"
    },
    {
        ", the use of plurality voting with multiple, single-winner constituencies to elect a multi-member body is often referred to as single-member district plurality or SMDP.  This combination is also variously referred to as winner-takes-all to contrast it with ": null
    },
    {
        "proportional representation": "Proportional Representation"
    },
    {
        " systems. This term is sometimes also used to refer to elections for multiple winners in a particular constituency using bloc voting.       Plurality voting is used for local and/or national elections in 43 of the 193 countries that are members of the ": null
    },
    {
        "United Nations": "United Nations"
    },
    {
        ". Plurality voting is particularly prevalent in the United Kingdom and former British colonies, including the United States, Canada and India.      In single winner plurality voting, each voter is allowed to vote for only one candidate, and the winner of the election is whichever candidate represents a plurality of voters, that is, whoever received the largest number of votes. This makes plurality voting among the simplest of all electoral systems for voters and vote counting officials.     In an election for a legislative body, with single-member seats, each voter in a given geographically-defined ": null
    },
    {
        "electoral district": "Constituency"
    },
    {
        " is entitled to vote for one candidate from a list of candidates competing to represent that district. Under the plurality system, the winner of the election then becomes the representative of the entire electoral district, and serves with representatives of other electoral districts.     In an election for a single seat, such as for ": null
    },
    {
        "president": "President"
    },
    {
        " in a ": null
    },
    {
        "presidential system": "Presidential System"
    },
    {
        ", the same style of ballot is used and the winner is the candidate who receives the largest number of votes.     In the ": null
    },
    {
        "two-round system": "Two-Round System"
    },
    {
        ", usually the two highest polling candidates in the first ballot progress to the second round ": null
    },
    {
        "Run-off": "Two-Round System"
    },
    {
        " ballot.     In a multiple member plurality election, with n seats available, the winners are the n candidates with the highest numbers of votes. The rules may allow the voter to vote for one candidate, or for up to n candidates, or maybe some other number.          Generally plurality ballots can be categorized into two forms. The simplest form is a blank ballot where the name of a candidate is written in by hand. A more structured ballot will list all the candidates and allow a mark to be made next to the name of a single candidate ; however a structured ballot can also include space for a ": null
    },
    {
        "write-in candidate": "Write-In Candidate"
    },
    {
        ".           The United Kingdom, like the United States and Canada, uses single-member districts as the base for ": null
    },
    {
        "national elections": "Uk General Election"
    },
    {
        ". Each electoral district chooses one ": null
    },
    {
        "member of parliament": "Member Of Parliament"
    },
    {
        ", i.e. the candidate who gets the most votes, whether or not they get 50% or more of the votes cast . In 1992, for example, a ": null
    },
    {
        "Liberal Democrat in Scotland": "Inverness, Nairn And Lochaber Elections"
    },
    {
        " won a seat with just 26% of the votes. This system of single-member districts with plurality winners tends to produce two large political parties; in countries with proportional representation there is not such a great incentive to vote for a large party, and that contributes to ": null
    },
    {
        "multi-party system": "Multi-Party System"
    },
    {
        "s.     Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland use the first past the post system for UK general elections, but use versions of proportional representation for elections to their own assemblies and parliaments. All of the UK has used a form of proportional representation for European Parliament elections.     The countries that inherited the British majoritarian system tend toward two large parties: one left, the other right, such as the U.S. Democrats and Republicans. Canada is an exception, with three major political parties consisting of the New Democratic Party which is to the left, the Conservative Party which is to the right and the Liberal Party which is slightly off center to the left. A fourth party that no longer has major party status is the separatist Bloc Québécois party, which is territorial and concentrated in Quebec. New Zealand used the British system, and it too yielded two large parties. It also left many New Zealanders unhappy, because other viewpoints were ignored, so its parliament in 1993 adopted a new electoral law, modelled on ": null
    },
    {
        "Germanys system": "Elections In Germanyelection System"
    },
    {
        " of proportional representation with a partial selection by constituencies. New Zealand soon developed a more complex party system. ": null
    },
    {
        "Roskin, Michael": "Michael Roskin"
    },
